\f1\b \cf3 ## **Current (Bad) Architecture:**
\f0\b0 \cf2 \
\'95 **Backend**: Filters to top 10 high-confidence correlations\
\'95 **Frontend**: Takes those 10 and filters them again with \cf4 correlation.confidence < 0.3\cf2 \
\

\f1\b \cf3 ## **Better Architecture Options:**
\f0\b0 \cf2 \
\

\f1\b \cf3 ### **Option 1: Backend does ALL filtering** (most common)
\f0\b0 \cf2 \
\'95 Backend: Apply confidence threshold, limit results, sort\
\'95 Frontend: Just display what backend sends (no filtering logic)\
\

\f1\b \cf3 ### **Option 2: Frontend does ALL filtering** (for dynamic UX)
\f0\b0 \cf2 \
\'95 Backend: Send all raw correlations\
\'95 Frontend: Filter/sort/limit based on user interactions (sliders, dropdowns)\
\

\f1\b \cf3 ### **Option 3: Hybrid** (current mess)
\f0\b0 \cf2 \
\'95 Both do filtering = duplicate logic + confusion\
\

\f1\b \cf3 ## **Why This Happened:**
\f0\b0 \cf2 \
The frontend was built when backend had simpler filtering, then backend got enhanced but frontend\
kept its own logic. Classic technical debt.\
\

\f1\b \cf3 ## **Best Practice:**
\f0\b0 \cf2 \
For your use case, 
\f1\b Option 1
\f0\b0  (backend filtering) is better because:\
\'95 Users don't need real-time filtering controls\
\'95 Reduces data transfer\
\'95 Single source of truth for business logic\
\'95 Simpler frontend code\
\
The current setup works but creates maintenance headaches when logic changes need to be updated \
in two places.\
\
