\cf4 > \cf2 Perfect! I've identified and fixed the issue. Here's what was happening:\
\

\f1\b \cf3 ## The Problem
\f0\b0 \cf2 \
The backend was updated to return correlation insights in a new object format:\

\f1\b javascript
\f0\b0 \
\cf4 \{\cf2 \
\cf4   triggers: [],\cf2 \
\cf4   helpers: [], \cf2 \
\cf4   trends: []\cf2 \
\cf4 \}\cf2 \
\
\
But the frontend \cf4 useCorrelations.js\cf2  hook was still expecting an array and trying to use \cf4 .filter()\cf2 \
directly on the \cf4 correlations\cf2  data, causing the "n.filter is not a function" error.\
\

\f1\b \cf3 ## The Solution
\f0\b0 \cf2 \
I updated the \cf4 useCorrelations.js\cf2  hook to:\
\
1. 
\f1\b Handle both formats
\f0\b0 : Added a compatibility layer that detects whether the backend returns an \
array (old format) or object (new format)\
\
2. 
\f1\b Convert to array
\f0\b0 : When the new object format is received, it flattens all correlations from \
\cf4 triggers\cf2 , \cf4 helpers\cf2 , and \cf4 trends\cf2  arrays into a single \cf4 allCorrelations\cf2  array\
\
3. 
\f1\b Maintain compatibility
\f0\b0 : All existing \cf4 .filter()\cf2  operations now work on \cf4 allCorrelations\cf2  instead \
of the raw \cf4 correlations\cf2  response\
\
4. 
\f1\b Preserve functionality
\f0\b0 : All the existing grouping, filtering, and statistical functions \
continue to work as expected\
\

\f1\b \cf3 ## Key Changes
\f0\b0 \cf2 \
\'95 Added \cf4 allCorrelations\cf2  array that handles both backend formats\
\'95 Updated all \cf4 .filter()\cf2 , \cf4 .some()\cf2 , and array operations to use \cf4 allCorrelations\cf2 \
\'95 Return \cf4 allCorrelations\cf2  as the main \cf4 correlations\cf2  data to maintain API compatibility\
\'95 No breaking changes to components that use this hook\
\
The fix has been committed and pushed, which will trigger an automatic deployment. The error \
should be resolved once the new frontend code is deployed and the browser cache is cleared.\
